There is no need to clean strings being passed as bindings because PDO parameter binding protects against SQL injection attacks. PDO does not support binding column names, so it cannot be used to specify column names that are not part of the query. By default, PDO will automatically bind any non-nullable parameters with their corresponding values, which means that if a user inputs a value for a non-nullable parameter, it will be bound to that value. This ensures that the query is safe from SQL injection attacks. However, if you want to ensure that the user input is validated before binding the parameter, you can use the `bindParam()` method to pass in a custom value instead of the default one. For example:

```php
$stmt = $pdo->prepare('SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = :id');
$stmt->bindParam(':id', $user_id);
$stmt->execute();
```

In this example, `:id` is replaced with the user ID passed in as a parameter. This ensures that the user input is validated before binding the parameter to the query.
